plan: In the initial practice rounds, focus on understanding the market mechanics and the behavior of other participants. Experiment with different order types and sizes. Observe the relationship between submitted orders, market prices, and dividends. Use the practice reflection to summarize observations and develop preliminary strategies for the main experiment.
insight: No significant insights yet, as this is the first round.

plan: For the next practice round, I will try submitting orders closer to the previous market price (14) to increase the likelihood of execution.  I will also vary the quantities to see how that affects the market.  Specifically, I will submit limit buy and sell orders bracketing the last closing price to learn about the spread.
insight: The first round suggests that either a) there were no other participants, or b) no one else submitted crossing orders.  The market did not clear any trades despite my orders existing on both sides. Further investigation is needed to understand the market dynamics. Buy and Sell orders MUST bracket the previous rounds closing price.

plan: Continue submitting limit buy and sell orders bracketing the last closing price (14). Will also place a buy order significantly below market price and a sell order significantly above to test the waters. Monitor market behavior to refine strategy for the main experiment. Forecast conservatively around the buyback price.
insight: No trades executed so far, suggesting lack of other participants or passive strategies. Buy/sell order spread strategy seems ineffective so far.  Need to gather more data in the next practice round.  Forecasts at 14 provide a base-case scenario given the terminal stock value.

plan:
Round 1: Establish baseline market behavior. Bracketing 14, with exploratory trades further from this price. 
Next few rounds: Analyze market reaction and adjust pricing strategy accordingly.  Refine forecast model based on observed prices and volume.
insight: Initial market depth is unknown. No insights from practice rounds due to lack of trades. Aim to learn from early trades.

plan:
Round 2-3: Aggressively widen bid-ask spread to gauge market depth. Continue to bracket expected value (14), but with larger deviations.  Begin collecting market price data to refine forecast model.
Next few rounds: Based on market behavior and observed price discovery, adjust trading strategy. Consider larger order sizes once market depth is understood. If the market is efficient, then revert to bracketing tighter around 14 once we have an idea of daily volatility.
insight: Market appears illiquid at round 1.  No clear price discovery yet.  Hypothesizing other participants are similarly cautious, bracketing 14, or waiting for more information.  Need to incentivize trading to understand market dynamics.

plan: Rounds 4-6: Continue to explore market depth with wide bid-ask spread, but also place limit orders closer to 14 to capture any deviations.  Begin to analyze if the high/low dividend rounds have any impact on price.  Monitor market volume for signs of increased participation. If market shows some liquidity, reduce spread size to optimize profit.  Start to formulate more sophisticated forecasting model based on realized prices and volumes.
insight: The market remains illiquid after three rounds, suggesting that most participants are behaving similarly.  Wide bid-ask spreads haven't incentivized trading yet.  Need to consider both exploring market depth and potentially capitalizing on small price fluctuations around 14 if any volume materializes. Price of 14.5 in round 2 is still too early to derive a trend from given no volume was transacted.

plan: Rounds 7-9: Tighten the bid-ask spread around 14 to try and capture small price fluctuations. Place limit BUY at 13 and SELL at 15 to see if any trades execute closer to the theoretical value.  Maintain wider orders to continue probing market depth (BUY at 11, SELL at 17). Continue to analyze market volume and prices to refine forecasting model. If no trades execute, I may widen the bracket around 14 and explore other ranges further out..
insight: Even with wider spreads, no trades were executed in rounds 1-3.  This reinforced the initial observation of market illiquidity. The small volume observed in round 3 without my orders being filled indicates potential competition around similar price points.  Tightening the spread around 14 is the next logical step to test for profitability, but maintaining some wider orders can still provide valuable information about market depth.

plan: Rounds 10-12: If the tighter spread (13-15) doesn't result in trades, I will incrementally widen the spread in subsequent rounds. If I do see trades at 13 or 15, I will increase volume at that price. Experiment with varying order sizes to see if this influences trade execution.  Continue to record and analyze market volume and prices in an effort to improve forecasting accuracy.
insight: Limited market activity observed so far, even with wider spreads.  Tightening around 14 is proving difficult and some orders may be too passive.  Need to find ways to be more aggressive with order prices without straying too far from the theoretical value.  Small volumes observed indicate potential market participants are active around the theoretical price and further reinforces my theory that arbitrage may be possible within this range.

plan: Rounds 13-15: If still no trades at the wider spread (11/17) I will analyze if there is a pattern to price changes from round to round (e.g always goes to 14.5 or some other value after 14). If so I will front-run that for a few rounds.  If not, revert to a tighter spread of 13/15 and increase order size to try and generate trading activity.
insight: Even widening the buy/sell spread hasn't resulted in executed trades. The market is more illiquid than initially anticipated. It's possible that most participants are passive or using a similar strategy, waiting for more significant price fluctuations.  Need to test for exploitable trends or patterns.

plan: Rounds 16-18: If still no trades with larger order sizes at 13/15, will alternate between buying and selling single shares at 14 to see if I can make any progress. Will also continue to observe market prices for any emerging patterns or deviations from 14 to inform future strategies. Will continue to monitor trading volume.
insight: Widening the spread and increasing order size did not result in any trades.  The market remains very illiquid.  Hypothesis: other participants are also being passive and/or using similar strategies. Will test smaller price differentials.

plan: Rounds 19-21: Will re-evaluate the market conditions and adjust strategies if necessary.  If the alternating buy/sell at 14 strategy doesn't produce results, will widen the spread again but with smaller order sizes (1 share).  If *that* doesn't produce results, I will need to reconsider my assumptions about other player behavior.
insight: Alternating single share buy/sell orders at 14 did not produce trades in rounds 8-15. The market is extraordinarily illiquid.  Will try widening the spread with small order sizes to see if any latent demand exists.

plan: Rounds 22-24: Will try to make more narrow buy/sell orders to see if that will lead to execution at 14. If this still fails to produce trades, I will re-evaluate the assumptions and try a strategy other than bracketing 14.
insight: Widening the spread did not produce trades. Reducing order sizes did not produce trades either.  The market continues to be surprisingly inactive, even after the practice rounds.  Either participants are extremely risk-averse/passive or they are simply not active during the early rounds. I've gotten zero fills so far. Bracketing a price of 14, which seems to be the market consensus.

plan: Rounds 25-30: Will further narrow the buy/sell orders to see if that leads to fills at 14.  If no fills, will then widen the spread to try to discover some price information from the market.  Still assuming that 14 is a reasonable price, given interest rate and dividend information.
insight: Still no fills, after narrowing spreads further, but now the volume has started to increase in the market, perhaps suggesting more activity will occur in the near future.
